summary:
Iran fired missiles at a Tel Aviv suburb, killing two people with shrapnel from the blasts. The attack followed Israeli killings of Ali Larijani and a militia commander. Israel struck central Beirut without warning, killing six Lebanese residents and injuring 24. Satellite images show burning ships in an Iranian port and destroyed buildings at a U.S. base damaged since the February 28 start of the three-week regional war. About 90 ships, including oil tankers, crossed the Strait of Hormuz as Iran exported millions of oil barrels. Israeli, Lebanese, and regional civilians are affected. Further retaliatory strikes are expected.

In Afghanistan, a Pakistani airstrike hit a Kabul drug rehabilitation center, killing dozens and possibly hundreds of civilians. The Afghan government vows retaliation. Separately in Nigeria, Boko Haram suicide bombers killed 23 people at a Maiduguri teaching hospital and two markets in Borno State. U.S. aid to Nigeria continues. In Kenya, nationwide floods during long rains caused five more deaths, raising the toll to 71. Kenyan residents are affected. Rescues continue, with implications for regional food security.

The EU proposed funds and technical aid for Ukraine to repair an oil pipeline central to a dispute with Hungary over aid. This affects European energy supplies. UK Prime Minister Starmer told Zelensky in London talks that international focus must remain on Ukraine despite the Iran conflict and signed a drone defense pact. Israel permitted over one million displaced Palestinians to cross a military zone back to northern Gaza after a hostage release deadlock ended. Chinese developer Vanke reported a huge loss amid the property crisis, affecting investors and global markets. NATO deployed its first response after a second Baltic Sea cable was severed in a suspected sabotage campaign."}
